e. I'm also verifying that all the key hints are captured in s1, looking for any gaps in the terminology around transaction timeouts, query timeouts, and the related exception handling. The hints look solid overall. `SQLException#getErrorCode` is already captured in s2, and s1's `SQLException` entry would still surface relevant results. s3 seems complete without needing additional class names. The coverage across all three sections appears comprehensive.\n\nNow I'm verifying the S9 warning—it checks out as a false positive since both the source and knowledge file have 3 h2 sections. The code example actually shows an improvement where an erroneous closing tag was removed from the original. Let me trace through the footnote [#seq3] content to make sure the knowledge file accurately reflects what the source states about exception code determination and configuration. The XML structure looks correct now with the malformed closing tag removed, and while the inline comments about transaction timeout seconds and error codes were omitted from the knowledge file, that's an acceptable trade-off since the property descriptions capture the essential information.\n\nLet me double-check the intro section though—the source includes a warning to confirm the 注意点 section before using this feature, which the knowledge file doesn't explicitly call out. But since the actual 注意点 content is present in the file, an AI agent would still find it, so this isn't a critical gap.\n\nOverall, the knowledge file appears solid with no significant issues.\n\nActually, I'm noticing something in the s1 section—the knowledge file includes the note about not checking timeouts at transaction end, but it's missing the reasoning behind that decision: response time to the client doesn't change, so prioritizing normal termination makes sense for usability. For a knowledge file, that \"why\" context could be valuable for an AI to understand the design rationale, even if it's not strictly required for the dec